  "notes": "Direct curl to cbi.ir/PolicyRates/policyrates_en.aspx is blocked by the same F5/TSPD JS bot-challenge documented elsewhere in this project (confirmed again this session: HTTP 200 but body is a TSPD 'Please enable JavaScript' challenge page, no real content). Retrieved instead via the Wayback Machine CDX API (https://web.archive.org/cdx/search/cdx?url=cbi.ir/PolicyRates*&output=json), same technique as the successful cbi-annual-review-wayback recovery. The CDX index returned 38 snapshots with distinct content digests spanning 2021-04-27 to 2026-02-17; each snapshot is a live-rendered HTML page (ASP.NET webform) showing a 'Year' dropdown filter and a table of the ~10-24 most recent weekly policy-rate readings for whichever year was selected at crawl time (not a full historical archive on one page). Fetched all 38 snapshot timestamps: 32 returned real content with the rate table (verified via string match on 'Interbank Market Rate' in each file), 2 returned CBI's TSPD bot-challenge page and were discarded (2026-01-07, 2026-02-17 — evidently even the Wayback crawler itself got blocked on later crawls as CBI's bot protection tightened), and 4 returned a generic 'Request Rejected'/WAF page (archive.org- or proxy-side rejection, 2 of them tied to a malformed source URL with a stray fullwidth paren '%EF%BC%89' appended — likely from a bad inbound link somewhere — and were discarded). Net: 32 HTML snapshots kept, each an authentic unmodified capture of the CBI page as archived by the Wayback Machine (raw files preserved as-downloaded per bookkeeping rules; no reformatting). Cross-snapshot extraction (ad hoc, not stored in data/raw) found 194 distinct dated weekly rows across the full set, covering 2021-02-13 through 2025-06-11 — the four rate series (Interbank Market Rate, Repo Cut-off Rate, Standing Lending Rate, Standing Deposit Rate) are stable/step-function-like within any given stretch, so this reconstructs the effective step-change history reasonably well, though gaps between snapshot dates mean not every individual week in that span is necessarily captured. A downstream processing step could parse all 32 files and deduplicate into a single time series CSV in data/processed/, but that was out of scope for this raw-download pass.",
